data.content:
## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

**Pattern identified:** Timeout enforcement — `Thread.Abort()` kills a thread that exceeds a time limit.

### Why this breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+. `Thread.ResetAbort()` is also gone (`SYSLIB0006`). The entire preemptive abort model is removed.

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        // CancellationTokenSource is IDisposable — always wrap in using
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            // Task.Run + WaitAsync gives us timeout enforcement
            // without Thread.Abort
            return Task.Run(work, cts.Token)
                       .WaitAsync(cts.Token)  // .NET 6+ API
                       .GetAwaiter()
                       .GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    // Preferred: async overload for modern callers
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout, CancellationToken externalToken = default)
    {
        using var cts = CancellationTokenSource
            .CreateLinkedTokenSource(externalToken);
        cts.CancelAfter(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await Task.Run(work, cts.Token)
                             .WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (!externalToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        // If externalToken was cancelled, OperationCanceledException
        // propagates as-is (correct behavior — caller requested cancellation)
    }
}
```

### If the work must cooperate with cancellation

The above stops *waiting*, but the delegate keeps running on the thread pool. For true cancellation, the work must accept a token:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

    try
    {
        return Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token)
                   .WaitAsync(cts.Token)
                   .GetAwaiter()
                   .GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

### Key pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Fire-and-forget work** | `Task.Run(work)` without cooperative cancellation means the delegate keeps running after timeout — it just isn't waited on. Unlike `Thread.Abort`, nothing forcibly stops it. |
| **`CancellationTokenSource` leak** | Always `using`/dispose. The `CancelAfter` timer leaks otherwise. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | Use `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` to only catch timeout — not external cancellation. |
| **Truly uncooperative code** | If the work is a long-running native/third-party call you can't modify, move it to a child `Process` and use `Process.Kill()`. There is no in-process equivalent of `Thread.Abort` in modern .NET. |
| **`ThreadAbortException` cleanup logic** | The original `ResetAbort` catch block had cleanup intent. In the migrated code, cleanup goes in `finally` or `CancellationToken.Register()` callbacks instead. |

### What was removed and why

| .NET Framework API | Replacement | Reason |
|----|----|----|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 6+ |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | `ThreadAbortException` is never thrown |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` | API removed (`SYSLIB0006`) |
| `new Thread()` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run()` | Thread pool is preferred; avoids manual thread management |
